This apartment is maintained by a real estate business not a single owner. This has pros and cons. The pros are that they have a staff that communicates very quickly and responds to your needs. When we first got there there were no air conditioning units and it was very hot but the host purchased and installed units within 48 hours of us notifying her. Likewise, when there was a substantial leak in one of the bedrooms one day, someone was there the next day to patch it up. The cons of such a situation, however, are that it doesn't really feel lived in and at times is very dorm-like. The furnitures and amenities are also very cheaply made and appear to just be temporary, cheap stand ins until the company is able to rent it out to a long term tenant. Ultimately, we left the experience with mixed feelings. The host was very responsive but given the premium price we paid to stay there it ultimately felt like we did not get the value we were expecting. If instead of $5000/month or $170/night the Host charged closer to $3500/month or $115/night I think that would be more representative of the apartment's value. Live and learn.
